{"id":"1603.09052","submitter":"Xueru Li","authors":"Xueru Li, Emil Bj\\\"ornson, Shidong Zhou and Jing Wang","title":"Massive MIMO with Multi-Antenna Users: When are Additional User Antennas\n  Beneficial?","comments":"6 pages, 3 figures. accepted by ICT'2016","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.IT math.IT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We analyze the performance of massive MIMO systems with $N$-antenna users.\nThe benefit is that $N$ streams can be multiplexed per user, at the price of\nincreasing the channel estimation overhead linearly with $N$. Uplink and\ndownlink spectral efficiency (SE) expressions are derived for any $N$, and\nthese are achievable using estimated channels and per-user-basis MMSE-SIC\ndetectors. Large-system approximations of the SEs are obtained. This analysis\nshows that MMSE-SIC has similar asymptotic SE as linear MMSE detectors,\nindicating that the SE increase from having multi-antenna users can be\nharvested using linear detectors. We generalize the power scaling laws for\nmassive MIMO to handle arbitrary $N$, and show that one can reduce the\nmultiplication of the pilot power and payload power as $\\frac{1}{M}$ where $M$\nis the number of BS antennas, and still notably increase the SE with $M$ before\nreaching a non-zero asymptotic limit. Simulations testify our analysis and show\nthat the SE increases with $N$. We also note that the same improvement can be\nachieved by serving $N$ times more single-antenna users instead, thus the\nadditional user antennas are particular beneficial for SE enhancement when\nthere are few active users in the system.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 30 Mar 2016 06:56:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-03-31"}
